subSubSection.paragraph:
Comments and character discussion.

Kieffer (
1905
)

recognized 

Anisepyris

primarily by the anterior carina of the pronotum (character 
20
), the transverse groove on the scutellum (
24
), and the number of flagellomeres of the antenna. Herein, we also include the following characters: head and eyes large and densely pilose (
12, 13
), the clypeus with an arched median carina (
5
), the pronotal disc with a foveolate groove in the posterior portion (
24
), and the notauli generally sinuous, fine and shallow (
31
). Often, the species of this genus are also shiny (
46
) and have a malar space that is margined by a carina (
6
). The body shape is similar to 

Chlorepyris

. Yet 

Anisepyris

can be more carinate and marked with fovea and grooves, and the tarsal claws are distinct; 

Chlorepyris

species do not have a carinate malar space.

Mesopleuron
(

Figs. 
4

C, 
4
F). It seems to be surrounded by the prepectal (
47
) and postpectal carina (
48
). Generally, the postpectal carina is closed and forms the lower fovea (
49, 50
); the mesopleural fovea is elongate (
52
) and, some of species has a triangular shape; the mesopleural pit is deep. The episternal groove is present (
55
) and scrobiculate (
56
) in some species, the sub-tegular groove is complete; the anterior-superior fovea (
53
) is rounded and deep, in median to large size (
54
).
